<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="154" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,334,679,705]" box="[189,334,679,705]" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,334,679,705]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="16" pageNumber="154" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,334,679,705]" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,910,725,752]" box="[189,910,725,752]" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">
HABITUS. Colour from pale to brownish, encrusting (
<figureCitation box="[802,896,725,751]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1852,1878]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,696,1802]" captionTargetId="figure-79@15.[189,1398,690,1814]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 3. Ephydatia fluviatilis (Linnaeus, 1759). A. Habitus (P059-211231-1). B. Spiculae, m = megasclere (P059-170902-2), g = gemmulosclere (P059-170902-1). C. Estimated megasclere size distribution within and between specimens, P059-170902-1 (solid line), P059-170902-2 (dashed), P059-170902-3 (dotted). Marks on the x-axis represent spiculae measured. Brackets correspond to ranges in literature (red = Tendal 1967b; blue = Penney &amp; Racek 1968; black = Evans &amp; Montagnes 2019)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6839819" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6839819/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,1399,791,888]" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">
SPICULAE. Megascleres and gemmuloscleres. Megascleres thin, smooth and acute oxeas (
<figureCitation box="[1286,1384,791,817]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1852,1878]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,696,1802]" captionTargetId="figure-79@15.[189,1398,690,1814]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 3. Ephydatia fluviatilis (Linnaeus, 1759). A. Habitus (P059-211231-1). B. Spiculae, m = megasclere (P059-170902-2), g = gemmulosclere (P059-170902-1). C. Estimated megasclere size distribution within and between specimens, P059-170902-1 (solid line), P059-170902-2 (dashed), P059-170902-3 (dotted). Marks on the x-axis represent spiculae measured. Brackets correspond to ranges in literature (red = Tendal 1967b; blue = Penney &amp; Racek 1968; black = Evans &amp; Montagnes 2019)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6839819" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6839819/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
), 250 μm (60–360 μm) long (
<figureCitation box="[522,615,826,852]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="15.[189,232,1852,1878]" captionTargetBox="[191,1398,696,1802]" captionTargetId="figure-79@15.[189,1398,690,1814]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Fig. 3. Ephydatia fluviatilis (Linnaeus, 1759). A. Habitus (P059-211231-1). B. Spiculae, m = megasclere (P059-170902-2), g = gemmulosclere (P059-170902-1). C. Estimated megasclere size distribution within and between specimens, P059-170902-1 (solid line), P059-170902-2 (dashed), P059-170902-3 (dotted). Marks on the x-axis represent spiculae measured. Brackets correspond to ranges in literature (red = Tendal 1967b; blue = Penney &amp; Racek 1968; black = Evans &amp; Montagnes 2019)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6839819" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6839819/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
), 7.5 μm (2–15 μm) wide. Very few gemmuloscleres found in the collected specimens; birotulated, often a spine on the shaft, 20 µm long and 25 μm wide.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="154" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,505,926,953]" box="[189,505,926,953]" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,505,926,953]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="16" pageNumber="154" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,505,926,953]" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">Distribution and habitats</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,1340,973,1000]" box="[189,1340,973,1000]" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">This species was only found in the Baltic, but was missing from the bona fide freshwater samples.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="154" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[189,303,1039,1065]" box="[189,303,1039,1065]" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,303,1039,1065]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="16" pageNumber="154" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,303,1039,1065]" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[188,1400,1085,1323]" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">
Five specimens from inland waters tentatively identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus, 1759:" authorityYear="1348" box="[916,1061,1085,1111]" class="Calcarea" family="Grantiidae" genus="Spongia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="16" pageNumber="154" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="fluviatilis">
<emphasis box="[916,1061,1085,1111]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">E. fluviatilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(based on megasclers only, lacking gemmulae) was reassigned to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Leidy" baseAuthorityYear="1851" box="[629,831,1120,1146]" class="Demospongiae" family="Spongillidae" genus="Eunapius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spongillida" pageId="16" pageNumber="154" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="fragilis">
<emphasis box="[629,831,1120,1146]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">Eunapius fragilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on bar-coding sequences and a re-scrutiny of spiculae, so there is a possibility that some previously reported specimens of this (in 
<collectingCountry box="[1240,1335,1155,1181]" name="Sweden" pageId="16" pageNumber="154">Sweden</collectingCountry>
) rare species may be misidentifications. It is quite possible, however, that it is present at greater depth at some of the sites, and thus missed in our study – the specimens from the Baltic were all from greater depths. We note, though, that 
<bibRefCitation author="Arndt" box="[442,594,1261,1287]" pageId="16" pageNumber="154" pagination="1 - 33" refId="ref12132" refString="Arndt W. 1932. Die Susswasserschwammfauna Schwedens, Finnlands und Danemarks. Arkiv for Zoologi 24 A (3): 1 - 33." type="journal article" year="1932">Arndt (1932)</bibRefCitation>
only listed specimens from seven sites, all but one site outside (south of) the present study area, so the lack of observations may reflect a rare occurrence.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
